      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely! The Maillard reaction occurs when reducing sugars and amino acids in the dough are exposed to heat, resulting in the formation of brown color compounds that give bread its flavorful crust. This reaction typically begins at around 140°C (284°F). Be cautious, as prolonging baking time or increasing temperature too much can lead to burning. For best results, bake your bread at temperatures around 190°C to 220°C (374°F to 428°F) and monitor the browning carefully.",
