    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indeed, it's more than just heat. The Maillard reaction is influenced by the ingredients in your bread dough. For instance, higher amounts of reducing sugar can speed up browning, while milk (which contains lactose) or ingredients like ascorbic acid can enhance the browning effect due to their sugar content. Proteins also play a role, as they need to interact with sugars to start the reaction. Adding a small amount of malted barley flour, which is high in enzymes, can also enhance browning due to the increased availability of reducing sugars from the malted grains. Thus, the type of flour, additional sugars, and other ingredients in your dough can all contribute to how quickly and intensely it browns during baking.",
